#### Conjugacy/conjugate priors
- ==A prior is *conjugate* **for the likelihood** function if the **posterior** is of the same form/type as the **prior**==
	- **computationally convenient priors** -> because we can algebrically calculate our **posterior distribution** by updating the parameters of the **prior distribution** 🚧
- **see** : [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Bayes' formula|Bayes' formula]] (posterior = prior... x likelihood)
- examples
	- Beta-Binomial conjugacy
	- Beta-Bernouilly conjugacy
	- Gamma-Exponential

![Pasted image 20220128214147.png](data:image/png;base64,)
=> See [[Topics/Machine Learning/People/Christopher Bishop|Bishop]] (2006) for more
- ℹ️ Every member of the exponential family has a conjugate prior

#### Sufficient statistics (statistique exhaustive)
- Discovered by Sir [[Topics/Mathematics/People/Ronald Fisher|Ronald Fisher]] in **1920**
- -> sufficient to represent a distribution / all the information needed to make inference
- eg. $\mu$ (the sample mean)
- **Fisher-Neyman factorization theorem** -> the statistics $\phi(x)$ are sufficient if we can write the pdf/pmf ([[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Probability density|Probability density]] function) in the form of $P(x|\theta)=h(x)g_\theta(\phi(x))$ where $h(x)$ is independent of $\theta$
- **exponential family** are a family of distributions that do not need to increase arbitrarily the number of parameters when we increase the number of data 🚧 => ==finite-dimensional sufficient statistics ?==
